IMA-223 / IMA-224 / IMA-225 — the _viewer.py half
=================================================

I do not own `squidmip/_viewer.py` (another agent holds it this wave), so the GUI change is
here rather than applied. Two patches in this stack have already failed to apply after
_viewer.py moved, so READ THE PROSE FIRST — the diff below is a convenience, the prose is the
specification. If the diff rejects, hand-apply from the prose; it is two edits and one new
method.

Verified, not guessed, TWICE — once at 493045d and again after rebasing onto main at db52703
(IMA-220, which moved _viewer.py by ~110 lines). Both times: `git apply` clean, then
`tests/test_viewer.py` 158 passed — 157 existing plus the added check below that opens all
three new tabs on the `squid_dataset` fixture. _viewer.py in the worktree is untouched; the
patch was reverted after each verification.

WHAT IT ADDS
------------
Three operator cards — Deconvolution, Background subtraction, Flat-field correction — each
opening a PREVIEW-ONLY tab. Nothing else in the viewer changes: the projector selector and the
CLI already read `available_projectors()`, so the three names appear there with no edit at all
once `squidmip/__init__.py` imports the operator modules (that part is already committed).

HUNK 1 — three entries in the `_OPERATIONS` tuple (~line 560 at db52703; FIND IT BY NAME,
not by line number — it has already moved twice)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Append three `Operation(...)` records after the existing `minerva` entry, INSIDE the closing
`)` of the tuple. Nothing else in that region moves.

  * `Operation("decon", "Deconvolution (Richardson-Lucy)", <blurb>, "_build_decon_tab")`
  * `Operation("bgsub", "Background subtraction", <blurb>, "_build_bgsub_tab")`
  * `Operation("flatfield", "Flat-field correction", <blurb>, "_build_flatfield_tab")`

The keys MUST be exactly `decon` / `bgsub` / `flatfield` — they are the registry names
`add_projector` uses in `squidmip/_decon.py`, `_background.py` and `_flatfield.py`, and
`run_operator` passes the key straight through to the engine. A typo here surfaces as a
KeyError from `_resolve_projector` at run time, not at import.

A comment above the three entries states WHY they get a different builder from mip/stitch:
they are plane-ops (`consumes=frozenset()`), so their output keeps z at full depth, and
`_output._validate_image` accepts Z == 1 only. Saving would fail loud. Loud is the right
behaviour; offering a Save button that always fails is not.

The console cards, the Process-well-plates menu and `_activate_operator`'s dispatch are all
already generic over `_OPERATIONS`, so this hunk alone is what makes the three features appear
in the UI. No dispatch edit anywhere.

HUNK 2 — three thin builders plus one generic `_build_plane_op_tab`, inserted between
`_build_stitch_tab` and `_build_run_tab` (~line 3285 at db52703 — again, find by name)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Insert, in this order, immediately after `_build_stitch_tab`'s `return` line and immediately
before `def _build_run_tab(self, op)`:

  a. `_build_decon_tab`  -> `self._build_plane_op_tab(_OPERATIONS_BY_KEY["decon"])`
  b. `_build_bgsub_tab`  -> `self._build_plane_op_tab(_OPERATIONS_BY_KEY["bgsub"])`
  c. `_build_flatfield_tab` -> the same, with `profile_chooser=True`. Flat-field is the one
     plane-op that cannot run without an argument: an illumination profile has no sane default
     (an identity field would silently do nothing while the UI said "corrected"), so the
     operator raises until one is loaded, and this flag is what loads it.
  d. `_build_plane_op_tab(self, op, profile_chooser=False)` — the new generic builder.

`_build_plane_op_tab` is deliberately `_build_run_tab` MINUS its top half. It reuses
`_op_tab_shell`, `_hline`, `_BTN_QSS`, `_COMBO_QSS`, `QSpinBox`, `QHBoxLayout`,
`QFileDialog` and `Path` — all already imported at the top of _viewer.py, so this hunk adds no
import. It contains:

  * (only when `profile_chooser`) a "Load illumination profile (.npy)…" button. It calls
    `squidmip.FlatfieldProfile.from_npy(path)` — which reads the stitcher's own
    `save_flatfield` format, so tilefusion profiles load directly — then
    `squidmip._flatfield.set_profile(profile)`. Two guards, both reporting into the label
    rather than raising into the event loop: a load failure prints the exception, and a
    profile whose shape does not match `reader.metadata["frame_shape"]` is REFUSED by name
    (loading a 2084x2084 profile onto a 3000px acquisition would otherwise raise mid-run, one
    well at a time). The Preview button stays disabled until a profile is accepted.
  * the same "First N wells" spinner as `_build_run_tab`, wired to
    `run_operator(op.key, out_parent=None, regions=self._order[:n], save=False)`.
  * NO destination picker, NO "Run on the whole plate", NO "Save previews to disk" checkbox —
    because there is nothing to write yet.
  * a note telling the user exactly that, plus "The raw acquisition is never modified" (the
    IMA-224 layer contract, said where the user can see it).

The preview path itself needs NO worker change. `_OperatorWorker`'s `save=False` branch already
streams `project_plate`, and `_on_well` already does `image[0, :, 0]` — for a plane-op that
indexes the FIRST z-plane, corrected, which is exactly what a preview should show. The
`(T, C, Nz, Y, X)` shape flows through untouched.

WHEN THE WRITER LEARNS Z > 1
----------------------------
`_build_plane_op_tab` deletes itself: point the three builders at `_build_run_tab` and drop it.
That is the whole migration, and it is why the preview-only restriction lives in ONE method
rather than being spread across three tabs.

A TEST TO ADD (tests/test_viewer.py owns the `qapp`/`stub_detail` fixtures, so it belongs
there, not in my files). This is the one I ran to verify the patch:

    def test_the_three_plane_op_tabs_build(qapp, stub_detail, squid_dataset):
        from squidmip import available_projectors
        root, _ = squid_dataset
        win = V.PlateWindow(None)
        win.ingest(str(root))
        for key in ("decon", "bgsub", "flatfield"):
            assert key in available_projectors()
            op = V._OPERATIONS_BY_KEY[key]
            win._open_op_tab(op.key, op.label, getattr(win, op.build_tab))
            assert key in win._op_tabs
        win.close()

